threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a MIPS-based IoT botnet agent, likely a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt malware families. The sample contains a large dictionary of hardcoded usernames and passwords (e.g., root, admin, Pon521, vizxv) in function sub_410898, which is used for Telnet/SSH brute-force attacks. It exhibits typical malicious behaviors such as scanning the /proc filesystem to identify and kill competing malware processes (sub_40d3ec), using busybox to download second-stage payloads via wget/tftp (sub_410490), and implementing persistence mechanisms by checking /proc/self/exe. Relevant IOCs include the GET request pattern 'GET /dlr.' and the use of 'busybox echo -ne' for dropping files.
